{"text": "When a turn around an object is made and a clove hitch is tied to the rope's own standing part, it produces either a buntline hitch or two half-hitches, depending on whether the turns of the clove hitch progress toward or away from the hitched object. Two-half hitches is also the capsized form of a granny knot.page=18 The buntline hitch itself is used as a necktie knot called the four-in-hand knot.\n\nThe clove hitch is also a part of a family of binding knots called millers' knots, which all start with a single hitch tied around an object.", "embedding": [-0.0074309083, 0.01625945, -0.18888202, -0.08490591, 0.026324902, -0.020514648, -0.012731058, -0.017991988, 0.010114914, -0.042634353, -0.06495598, 0.016041385, 0.07454784, -0.03202565, 0.06528542, -0.024585022, 0.005286618, -0.043362927, 0.05033735, 0.015905961, -0.047166184, 0.0073824385, -0.01414942, -0.017450808, -0.008714105, 0.01335287, -0.03155016, 0.03522443, -0.0018177512, 0.019552372, 0.007856153, -0.031424366, -0.018945714, -0.028287606, -0.08894724, -0.03738066, 0.028804462, -0.007769325, 0.0036419218, -0.0049527828, 0.05137727, 0.01338244, -0.0031897302, -0.013259662, 0.047209725, -0.02725922, 0.07200091, 0.039751653, 0.07753737, 0.008985371, 0.017672831, -0.027457103, 0.0017621595, -0.037962742, 0.044868838, 0.011933398, 0.05516087, 0.05462345, 0.0524401, -0.01587148, -0.011313359, 0.08537631, -0.024932709, 0.09239318, 0.059390638, -0.031699385, -0.04154712, 0.05244097, 0.041128285, 0.012180662, 0.022878746, -0.021614015, 0.034000244, -0.003698927, -0.07427276, 0.053215206, -0.019614872, 0.009982375, -0.017420262, 0.012093233, 0.022760829, 0.0024100095, 0.0035545728, 0.014736047, 0.01591387, 0.02776179, -0.03870747, -0.031841524, -0.011626272, 0.03228073, 0.023588702, 0.044259913, 0.035082508, 0.035336733, -0.03636106, 0.011314881, -0.024590284, 0.016162878, -0.026217671, -0.025078386, -0.062946655, -0.0018313216, 0.037813198, 0.0043533873, 0.007207149, 0.016452316, -1.7373244e-05, -0.02219